To explain ret further, let look at this small example
First, returning from a Procedure: 
; --- MAIN PROGRAM ---
main PROC
    mov rcx, 5          ; Put 5 in RCX (Standard 1st argument in Windows)
    
    call SquareIt       ; 1. Pushes the address of the next line (mov [res], rax) 
                        ;    onto the stack, then jumps to 'SquareIt'.

    mov [result], rax   ; 4. Execution resumes here. RAX now contains 25.
    ret                 ; Exit main
main ENDP

; --- SUBROUTINE ---
SquareIt PROC
    mov rax, rcx        ; Copy input (5) to RAX
    imul rax, rax       ; RAX = 5 * 5 = 25
    
    ret                 ; 3. Pops the return address from the stack and 
                        ;    jumps back to the instruction after the 'call'.
SquareIt ENDP

The different is, it is not return 25 (value in rax), it pops whatever is on top of the stack and puts it directly into the RIP, which is the address of original caller of this function
and value in rax is kept during this process and can be processed by original function (which in this example, is saved to result)

So in this example, we should also explain call, but as explain above, it pushes the address of the very next line (the "return address") onto the stack.
then jumps (changes RIP) to SquareIt location.
Which then can be ret to go back to the original caller !

